00:01:14.370 --> 00:01:17.160
In fact, most of the
characters on That '70s Show

00:01:17.160 --> 00:01:20.280
had clearly defined narrative
real estate that they lived in.

00:01:20.280 --> 00:01:22.890
But Donna was a bit
more loosely defined

00:01:22.890 --> 00:01:24.870
early on in the
show, which gave her

00:01:24.870 --> 00:01:26.490
more room to grow and change.

00:01:26.490 --> 00:01:28.500
Donna was literally
and figuratively

00:01:28.500 --> 00:01:31.600
the girl next door in the show,
but she was also so much more

00:01:31.600 --> 00:01:32.100
than that.

00:01:32.100 --> 00:01:34.650
She was a complicated person
with a distinct background

00:01:34.650 --> 00:01:36.660
viewpoint and wry
sense of humor.

00:01:36.660 --> 00:01:37.650
Oh, believe me, Donna.

00:01:37.650 --> 00:01:40.440
I'd love to go, but
Red said I can't, and--

00:01:40.440 --> 00:01:43.320
well, he can kick my ass, so--

00:01:43.320 --> 00:01:45.570
Eric, I can kick your ass.

00:01:45.570 --> 00:01:48.240
We also got to witness
Topher Grace's Eric Forman

00:01:48.240 --> 00:01:51.060
grow and mature through his
relationship with Donna.

00:01:51.060 --> 00:01:54.750
They complemented each other and
yet were also polar opposites.

00:01:54.750 --> 00:01:57.000
That was the joy of the
early seasons of the show,

00:01:57.000 --> 00:01:59.280
seeing these two
seemingly unlikely lovers

00:01:59.280 --> 00:02:01.080
bounce off of each
other and learn

00:02:01.080 --> 00:02:02.430
and grow from their mistakes.

00:02:02.430 --> 00:02:04.680
This dynamic, and all
of its complexities,

00:02:04.680 --> 00:02:07.230
are laid out in the
show's inaugural episode,

00:02:07.230 --> 00:02:10.050
the climax of which is Donna
and Eric Forman sitting

00:02:10.050 --> 00:02:12.090
on the hood of a
flashy Vista Cruiser

00:02:12.090 --> 00:02:14.850
that Eric's father explicitly
told him not to take out

00:02:14.850 --> 00:02:18.060
of town, and yet, thanks to
Donna's encouragement, Eric

00:02:18.060 --> 00:02:21.390
and the gang use the car to
attend a Todd Rundgren concert.

00:02:21.390 --> 00:02:24.510
Coming down off the high of
this youthful rebellion, Donna

00:02:24.510 --> 00:02:27.180
and Eric bond, simmering
with romantic tension.

00:02:27.180 --> 00:02:30.270
In some ways, Donna is presented
as the manic pixie dream girl

00:02:30.270 --> 00:02:33.570
trope, but Prepon's performance
is so self-assured and nimbly

00:02:33.570 --> 00:02:35.700
humorous that the rote
elements of her roll's

00:02:35.700 --> 00:02:38.040
initial characterization
pale in comparison

00:02:38.040 --> 00:02:39.450
to the magic on the screen.

00:02:39.450 --> 00:02:41.920
The pilot climaxes with the
quintessential high school

00:02:41.920 --> 00:02:42.420
moment--

00:02:42.420 --> 00:02:44.580
Eric Forman not
seizing the opportunity

00:02:44.580 --> 00:02:45.840
and going in for the kiss.

00:02:45.840 --> 00:02:47.190
So what does Donna do?

00:02:47.190 --> 00:02:48.900
She chooses to take
the initiative,

00:02:48.900 --> 00:02:52.050
sealing their burgeoning romance
with a single good night kiss.

00:02:52.050 --> 00:02:53.460
What was that for?

00:02:53.460 --> 00:02:55.920
I just wanted to see
what it was like.

00:02:55.920 --> 00:02:58.684
What was it like?

00:02:58.684 --> 00:02:59.930
You were there.

00:02:59.930 --> 00:03:02.030
Under normal sitcom
narrative construction,

00:03:02.030 --> 00:03:04.280
this would have happened
dozens of episodes

00:03:04.280 --> 00:03:06.590
and countless seasons
into the run of a show.

00:03:06.590 --> 00:03:09.660
The Office took four seasons
to finally get Jim and Pam

00:03:09.660 --> 00:03:10.160
together.

00:03:10.160 --> 00:03:11.960
For New Girl, it
took six seasons

00:03:11.960 --> 00:03:14.030
to finally seal the
deal with Nick and Jess.

00:03:14.030 --> 00:03:17.420
A normal sitcom wants to
build an emotional investment

00:03:17.420 --> 00:03:19.400
in the two leads'
emotional dynamic

00:03:19.400 --> 00:03:21.620
prior to eventually
getting them together.

00:03:21.620 --> 00:03:23.930
This is the pilot
of That '70s Show.

00:03:23.930 --> 00:03:25.910
We understand from
the jump that Donna

00:03:25.910 --> 00:03:28.040
isn't going to be your
average love interest.

00:03:28.040 --> 00:03:30.440
She's going to be an
equal partner in the show

00:03:30.440 --> 00:03:31.430
as it develops.

00:03:31.430 --> 00:03:34.220
And over the first season,
we see countless examples

00:03:34.220 --> 00:03:36.470
of Donna's complexities
and intricately

00:03:36.470 --> 00:03:39.080
woven emotional life
written across the series.

00:03:39.080 --> 00:03:41.300
Like in episode seven of
the first season where

00:03:41.300 --> 00:03:44.120
Donna chooses to sing and
dance the night away with Eric,

00:03:44.120 --> 00:03:46.160
recreating the ABBA
music they just

00:03:46.160 --> 00:03:49.310
witnessed together as a means
of helping them both evolve.

00:03:49.310 --> 00:03:52.190
Donna and Eric quickly become
the central narrative nucleus

00:03:52.190 --> 00:03:53.600
that the show revolves around.

00:03:53.600 --> 00:03:55.970
They are the emotional
heart of the program.

00:03:55.970 --> 00:03:58.370
The show does a masterful
job of illustrating

00:03:58.370 --> 00:04:02.300
why someone in Donna's position
needs, enjoys, and loves

00:04:02.300 --> 00:04:03.650
someone like Eric Forman.

00:04:03.650 --> 00:04:06.440
It all stems back to her
relationship with her parents--

00:04:06.440 --> 00:04:07.460
Bob and Midge.

00:04:07.460 --> 00:04:11.030
Midge is a free spirit, and
Bob is more of a loud out there

00:04:11.030 --> 00:04:11.750
ladies man.

00:04:11.750 --> 00:04:13.550
Midge ends up
leaving Bob since she

00:04:13.550 --> 00:04:15.350
was unhappy with
being a housewife,

00:04:15.350 --> 00:04:18.079
and Bob subscribed to more
of the man of the house

00:04:18.079 --> 00:04:19.310
sensibilities of the time.

00:04:19.310 --> 00:04:23.030
When Donna sees in Eric is the
exact opposite, a progressive

00:04:23.030 --> 00:04:25.700
with a non-threatening physique
and an intricate knowledge

00:04:25.700 --> 00:04:28.140
of Star Wars, and this
is charming to her.

00:04:28.140 --> 00:04:30.620
Donna goes through five
seasons of characterization.

00:04:30.620 --> 00:04:33.260
She has ups and downs,
break ups with Eric,

00:04:33.260 --> 00:04:36.290
