00:04:56.750 --> 00:04:58.580
In season five,
they get engaged.

00:04:58.580 --> 00:05:01.490
However, Eric stands Donna
up on the wedding day only

00:05:01.490 --> 00:05:03.230
to return saying he was scared.

00:05:03.230 --> 00:05:06.525
All I knew was that I--

00:05:06.525 --> 00:05:09.020
Donna, I think we were about
to make a huge mistake.

00:05:09.020 --> 00:05:11.270
I'm sure there's a good
version of this storyline that

00:05:11.270 --> 00:05:13.400
painted Donna in an
empowering light,

00:05:13.400 --> 00:05:15.620
but it just feels
weird and wrong

00:05:15.620 --> 00:05:18.200
that the show is doing
all of this to her

00:05:18.200 --> 00:05:21.290
and that she's not the person
dictating how things turn out.

00:05:21.290 --> 00:05:24.320
Because that's been basically
her role the entire show.

00:05:24.320 --> 00:05:27.410
This goes all the way back to
the pilot when she's the one

00:05:27.410 --> 00:05:29.450
to initiate that first kiss.

00:05:29.450 --> 00:05:32.060
During season seven, Topher
Grace and Ashton Kutcher

00:05:32.060 --> 00:05:33.620
were negotiating
to leave the show

00:05:33.620 --> 00:05:36.410
to pursue other opportunities,
and by the time season

00:05:36.410 --> 00:05:38.990
eight rolled around, the
narrative runway was already

00:05:38.990 --> 00:05:40.310
out from underneath the show.

00:05:40.310 --> 00:05:42.680
Because Topher Grace
wasn't going to be there,

00:05:42.680 --> 00:05:45.050
Eric Forman had decided
to take a gap year

00:05:45.050 --> 00:05:47.480
and move to Africa,
leaving Donna in the lurch

00:05:47.480 --> 00:05:50.240
despite the fact that she had
deferred her college choices

00:05:50.240 --> 00:05:51.440
in order to be with him.

00:05:51.440 --> 00:05:55.040
Kelso is also only in five
episodes of the final season.

00:05:55.040 --> 00:05:56.300
It's just a train wreck.

00:05:56.300 --> 00:05:58.520
The idea of Eric hurting
Donna in this way

00:05:58.520 --> 00:06:01.220
is counter to both of the
establishing characters.

00:06:01.220 --> 00:06:04.430
Him doing it violates the exact
reasons why she loves him.

00:06:04.430 --> 00:06:07.040
Therefore, in later
episodes where he returns,

00:06:07.040 --> 00:06:08.510
she would never take him back.

00:06:08.510 --> 00:06:11.000
It's very apparent from the
beginning of season eight

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:13.880
that the showrunners did not
know what to do with Donna.

00:06:13.880 --> 00:06:15.680
They were trapped
into only viewing her

00:06:15.680 --> 00:06:18.200
through the Eric-shaped
box they had put her in.

00:06:18.200 --> 00:06:20.450
After initially trying
to introduce a new Eric

00:06:20.450 --> 00:06:23.180
stand in named Charlie, they
wrote him out of the show.

00:06:23.180 --> 00:06:25.760
Therefore Josh Myers was
cast as Randy Pearson.

00:06:25.760 --> 00:06:27.950
The showrunners decided
to introduce Randy

00:06:27.950 --> 00:06:30.230
as equal parts Eric and Kelso.

00:06:30.230 --> 00:06:32.610
He could fill the narrative
shoes of both of them

00:06:32.610 --> 00:06:35.210
but also be presented as
a potential love interest

00:06:35.210 --> 00:06:38.150
to Donna, which is as
horrible as it sounds.

00:06:38.150 --> 00:06:41.000
Randy's whole thing is that
everyone thinks he's perfect.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:42.110
Even Red likes him.

00:06:42.110 --> 00:06:44.152
They taught me how to play
their games of chance.

00:06:44.152 --> 00:06:46.277
Donna, must be nice to
finally have a boyfriend who

00:06:46.277 --> 00:06:48.770
can swing that sledgehammer
and hit that little black thing

00:06:48.770 --> 00:06:50.370
past-- seriously hit it.

00:06:50.370 --> 00:06:53.313
And so that has to mean
that Donna would immediately

00:06:53.313 --> 00:06:54.230
fall in love with him.

00:06:54.230 --> 00:06:54.730
Right?

00:06:54.730 --> 00:06:57.260
It's not like there's seven
previous seasons where

00:06:57.260 --> 00:06:58.940
we learn that Donna
doesn't want to be

00:06:58.940 --> 00:07:01.490
with an over the top
ladies man like her father.

00:07:01.490 --> 00:07:04.700
Season eight just nerfs all of
Donna's character development.

00:07:04.700 --> 00:07:07.280
Even early on in the season
when Eric is in Africa

00:07:07.280 --> 00:07:09.620
and he's regularly calling
his mother on the telephone,

00:07:09.620 --> 00:07:10.820
he never calls Donna.

00:07:10.820 --> 00:07:12.440
So I asked Mrs.
Foreman is he OK,

00:07:12.440 --> 00:07:15.110
and she said yeah, because
he called her last night.

00:07:15.110 --> 00:07:17.780
She even stays up through the
night in one episode waiting

00:07:17.780 --> 00:07:19.460
for him to call, even
though he doesn't.

00:07:19.460 --> 00:07:21.560
In a season filled
with terrible ideas

00:07:21.560 --> 00:07:23.490
like Jackie and Fez
should get together

00:07:23.490 --> 00:07:25.310
and what if Hyde
marries a stripper,

00:07:25.310 --> 00:07:29.510
the way Donna is treated is
both the most subtly horrible

00:07:29.510 --> 00:07:33.180
and the most frustrating.

00:07:33.180 --> 00:07:35.860
He had to run the class.

00:07:35.860 --> 00:07:37.620
So I'm going to go grab a beer.

00:07:37.620 --> 00:07:40.200
Following closely behind
the incomprehensible Donna

00:07:40.200 --> 00:07:42.990
and Randy romance storyline
for strangest subplot

00:07:42.990 --> 00:07:45.360
involving Donna ever is
the running narrative

00:07:45.360 --> 00:07:47.190
all throughout the
final season that

00:07:47.190 --> 00:07:50.370
sees Kitty and Donna become
estranged due to some mutually

00:07:50.370 --> 00:07:51.420
misplaced anger.

00:07:51.420 --> 00:07:54.030
This doesn't seem like anything
that would ever happen.

00:07:54.030 --> 00:07:56.430
Donna might as well be Kitty's
daughter at this point,

00:07:56.430 --> 00:07:59.520
and the whole season still
takes place in their basement.

00:07:59.520 --> 00:08:01.350
Having Kitty and
Donna be estranged

00:08:01.350 --> 00:08:04.110
but then having her in
the basement every episode

00:08:04.110 --> 00:08:05.610
feels forced and wrong.

00:08:05.610 --> 00:08:08.640
And to top it all off, their
big reconciliation in the finale

00:08:08.640 --> 00:08:11.550
just feels completely
hollow and unearned.

00:08:11.550 --> 00:08:13.770
Like everything in
season eight, it just

00:08:13.770 --> 00:08:16.380
happens because it
apparently needs to happen.

00:08:16.380 --> 00:08:18.150
By the final episode
of the season,

00:08:18.150 --> 00:08:21.210
when Eric finally returns and
he and Donna get back together,

00:08:21.210 --> 00:08:22.500
it's too little too late.

00:08:22.500 --> 00:08:25.350
The show has just belly flopped,
dragged Donna through the mud,

00:08:25.350 --> 00:08:28.020
and completely ruined the
beautifully unique character

00:08:28.020 --> 00:08:30.210
that it spent all of
that time developing.

00:08:30.210 --> 00:08:32.130
It's really a shame
how That '70s Show

00:08:32.130 --> 00:08:35.010
took one of the best and most
tightly plotted characters

00:08:35.010 --> 00:08:37.860
and then just said what
if she dated Randy.

00:08:37.860 --> 00:08:39.820
Well, that's all we have today.

